AWS Infrastructure Summary
1. Regions
A Region is a physical geographic area (e.g., US-East-1) containing a cluster of data centers. They are isolated from one another to ensure fault tolerance and help with data residency compliance.

2. Availability Zones (AZs)
An AZ consists of one or more discrete data centers within a Region. Each has redundant power, cooling, and networking. They are separated by miles to prevent a single local disaster from taking down an entire Region.

3. Global Infrastructure
The worldwide network of Regions, AZs, and Edge Locations. This includes a private, high-capacity fiber backbone that connects all AWS services globally for low-latency performance.

4. High Availability (HA)
A design goal to ensure a system is always operational. In AWS, this is achieved by Multi-AZ deployments—running your application in two or more AZs simultaneously so that if one fails, the others take over with no downtime.
